00:36:00,692 --> 00:36:02,152
- Yeah.
- And Dave Pate took it and said,

670
00:36:02,527 --> 00:36:04,337
“No, I'm just gonna
follow exactly what the board did.

671
00:36:04,729 --> 00:36:08,948
As complete single panel as that was,
I'm just gonna do that."

672
00:36:09,701 --> 00:36:12,421
And all you see is a little jiggle
in the butt and that's it.

673
00:36:16,374 --> 00:36:17,924
The music in this sequence
is really fun, too.

674
00:36:18,309 --> 00:36:20,479
It has kind of a retro...
kind of kung fu feel.

675
00:36:20,945 --> 00:36:24,165
Originally, we had a version of music
that was much more traditional.

676
00:36:24,783 --> 00:36:28,502
And it just gave the scene a real,
sort of, tonally down.

677
00:36:29,187 --> 00:36:31,707
And this is supposed to be
a fun conversation

678
00:36:32,223 --> 00:36:35,383
where he's trying to assert his point
that kung fu is not dead.

679
00:36:35,994 --> 00:36:38,394
And I think Hans was
there late one night...

680
00:36:38,897 --> 00:36:40,447
- It was very late, I think.
- It was very late.

681
00:36:40,832 --> 00:36:43,082
We were sitting there, kind of
being a little punchy after a while.

682
00:36:43,568 --> 00:36:48,608
He said, "I got an idea.” And he
played this and it was just... Oh, man.

683
00:36:49,474 --> 00:36:50,404
Wasn't this Lauren's cue?

684
00:36:50,709 --> 00:36:52,109
- I think it was, yeah.
- 1 think it was Lauren's cue.

685
00:36:52,477 --> 00:36:53,557
She just really brought this

686
00:36:54,045 --> 00:36:54,945
whole fun energy to the scene.

687
00:36:55,246 --> 00:36:57,236
Yeah, it's
very retro martial arts movie.

688
00:36:57,682 --> 00:36:58,881
Yeah.

689
00:36:59,718 --> 00:37:03,817
That shot right there
with boss wolf is Rodolphe.

690
00:37:04,556 --> 00:37:05,816
- 1 could tell.
- That was terrific.

691
00:37:06,157 --> 00:37:08,967
I wasn't even animation and when I saw
this shot in lighting, I was like...

692
00:37:09,527 --> 00:37:11,607
- "That's Rodolphe.”
- It looks just like him.

693
00:37:12,731 --> 00:37:14,461
They filmed you doing this.

694
00:37:14,866 --> 00:37:18,116
Helped the animator get that, and
it's exactly your facial expression,

695
00:37:18,737 --> 00:37:21,957
the way you bob your shoulders.
Oh, my goodness.

696
00:37:25,110 --> 00:37:26,400
Oh, the rickshaw.

697
00:37:26,745 --> 00:37:28,295
This is one of the early scenes,
one of the early ideas

698
00:37:28,680 --> 00:37:31,080
for the big city rickshaw chase,
sort of a car chase idea.

699
00:37:31,583 --> 00:37:33,753
Yeah, the idea of having
a car chase in ancient China

700
00:37:34,219 --> 00:37:36,029
with no engines was quite challenging,

701
00:37:36,454 --> 00:37:39,234
but made for a cool idea
for an action sequence.

702
00:37:39,791 --> 00:37:41,541
But we cover, pretty much,
half the city.

703
00:37:41,960 --> 00:37:46,060
Yeah. This city was built for the
rickshaw chase, in a lot of respects.

704
00:37:47,465 --> 00:37:50,625
We figured out all the technology
to create the city,

705
00:37:51,236 --> 00:37:52,546
you know, because of this.

706
00:37:52,904 --> 00:37:55,864
Yeah, you and Damon would sit there
and you plotted out

707
00:37:56,441 --> 00:38:01,241
every single block that we could use,
every eyeline that we were gonna see.

708
00:38:02,080 --> 00:38:03,890
It was insanely complicated.

709
00:38:04,315 --> 00:38:06,015
And making sure that we had
all the elevations

710
00:38:06,417 --> 00:38:08,346
- to make all these moments work...
- Yeah.

711
00:38:08,787 --> 00:38:10,866
- Look how vast that city is.
- It's huge.

712
00:38:11,322 --> 00:38:12,692
- And that's all practical.
- Yep.

713
00:38:13,024 --> 00:38:14,894
That's not matte painting.
It's a real city.

714
00:38:15,927 --> 00:38:17,657
And that's something we never
could've done in the first movie.

715
00:38:18,062 --> 00:38:21,372
No. And I think for...
and it pays off in stereo again,

716
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:26,040
where you really just believe
the whole thing. I mean, it all works.

717
00:38:26,771 --> 00:38:30,551
Didn't, on the first movie, when Tai
Lung and Po is on that firecracker cart,

718
00:38:31,242 --> 00:38:34,902
there was like one city block
and we could barely get that.

719
00:38:35,547 --> 00:38:38,827
Yeah. Yeah, the technology's gotten
better, computers have gotten fast...

720
00:38:39,450 --> 00:38:42,960
You know, just in three years, you know,
what happened with the technology

721
00:38:43,621 --> 00:38:47,341
- allowed us to go crazy, really.
- Yeah.

722
00:38:48,459 --> 00:38:50,359
This is a moment I very much enjoy.

723
00:38:50,795 --> 00:38:54,605
I think it’s one of those, again,
one of those cranky weekend thoughts

724
00:38:55,300 --> 00:38:57,960
where I needed to have Tigress
hit Po in the butt

725
00:38:58,503 --> 00:39:01,543
and create a firestream for the inertia.

726
00:39:02,140 --> 00:39:04,279
Yeah, that's great.
Like a sonic boom moment there.

727
00:39:04,776 --> 00:39:09,526
Yeah, and that beautiful effect from
afar of that firestream is amazing.

728
00:39:10,348 --> 00:39:13,948
Yeah. And the close-up shockwave
with the air bending, then refracting,

729
00:39:14,586 --> 00:39:16,986
you know, what you're seeing,
it just really adds to that moment

730
00:39:17,488 --> 00:39:19,567
before they jettison Po down the street.

731
00:39:20,024 --> 00:39:22,634
Didn't Lawrence have to look
at a bunch of shots of planes?

732
00:39:23,161 --> 00:39:26,471
There was a lot of sonic boom footage
we were looking at.

733
00:39:27,098 --> 00:39:28,528
- That was really fun.
- Yeah.

734
00:39:28,900 --> 00:39:32,330
Just beautiful research
gone to a butt-hit.

735
00:39:32,971 --> 00:39:33,931
Yeah.

736
00:39:34,239 --> 00:39:37,309
That's Philippe, again,
that animated that. Philippe Le Brun.

737
00:39:37,909 --> 00:39:40,399
This is a great animation
thing here, too. Just...

738
00:39:40,912 --> 00:39:43,812
- Yeah.
- l love the timing of that hit, there.

739
00:39:44,382 --> 00:39:46,082
Yeah. Bang!

740
00:39:46,451 --> 00:39:49,231
It's like pancake batter hitting
a counter. It's like, splat!

741
00:39:49,787 --> 00:39:51,627
Everybody in the theater
always goes, "Ooh!"

742
00:39:52,056 --> 00:39:54,546
Everybody feels that.
The timing's perfect.

743
00:39:55,059 --> 00:39:56,729
For it to all be in wide, as well.

744
00:39:57,161 --> 00:39:58,421
Yeah.

745
00:39:59,264 --> 00:40:00,964
There's some great crowd work here
with the wolves,

746
00:40:01,366 --> 00:40:03,006
the wolf army and the movement
of those characters.

747
00:40:03,401 --> 00:40:06,471
Again, we never could have had this
in the first movie.

748
00:40:07,071 --> 00:40:10,531
This many characters in a shot and
you can't tell which ones are crowd

749
00:40:11,142 --> 00:40:13,361
- and which ones are main.
- Right.

750
00:40:13,845 --> 00:40:15,625
They're all very carefully integrated

751
00:40:16,047 --> 00:40:20,147
and it just gives that sort of threat
that they're surrounded.

752
00:40:20,885 --> 00:40:23,285
This was tricky to figure out
how to actually lock these guys up

753
00:40:23,788 --> 00:40:25,598
because they're all such
strange creatures.

754
00:40:27,091 --> 00:40:29,701
I think I had Jason build, like,
four or five different sets of manacles

755
00:40:30,228 --> 00:40:32,128
and they were all chained together
at one point,

756
00:40:32,563 --> 00:40:34,143
and it just got too crazy, so...

757
00:40:34,532 --> 00:40:36,962
Wasn't it a case of "If we chain them
together, it would be the complexity

758
00:40:37,468 --> 00:40:40,538
- of an entire battle sequence"?
- Yeah, so that was out.

759
00:40:41,272 --> 00:40:45,052
Now the gorilla just has a stick
with a hook on it and he grabs Po.

760
00:40:45,743 --> 00:40:47,173
And then sort of everybody else follows,

761
00:40:47,545 --> 00:40:49,535
so they didn't have to be
all chained together.

762
00:40:49,981 --> 00:40:53,791
This is a beautiful moment to see,
really, what that rig is capable of

763
00:40:54,485 --> 00:40:57,065
and the cloth and...
cloth and feathers working together.

764
00:40:57,588 --> 00:40:58,728
The peacock fighting,

765
00:40:59,057 --> 00:41:02,156
all that beautiful choreography
that you did, it's just so gorgeous.

766
00:41:02,760 --> 00:41:06,300
We had to cut it down a lot, but...
just to hit more of a story point,

767
00:41:06,965 --> 00:41:13,145
but, yeah, it was fun to just make a
showcase of his elegance and still being

768
00:41:14,339 --> 00:41:17,909
- very fierce and dangerous, but...
- This was actually a tough call

769
00:41:18,576 --> 00:41:21,676
because we actually animated
a pass of that sequence before.

770
00:41:22,280 --> 00:41:24,800
And it was a talking sequence
where they were just talking,

771
00:41:25,316 --> 00:41:28,975
standing and talking, and it did not
feel like it was interesting.

772
00:41:29,654 --> 00:41:32,554
You know, it was beautifully animated,
but just was not interesting.

773
00:41:33,124 --> 00:41:36,843
And it didn't show his issue.
It didn't show his fear very well.

774
00:41:37,528 --> 00:41:39,928
We showed his fear, at one point,
by having him

775
00:41:40,398 --> 00:41:42,918
practicing in the mirror,
seeing how he looked.

776
00:41:43,434 --> 00:41:46,394
And then decided to go with
a little bit more action slant on it.

777
00:41:46,971 --> 00:41:49,051
- Not badass enough.
- Yeah. It wasn't very cool.

778
00:41:49,507 --> 00:41:51,237
It definitely makes it more of a cage.

779
00:41:51,642 --> 00:41:53,752
Like he's ready for a fight
and he's practicing

780
00:41:54,212 --> 00:41:56,352
and it builds that moment
when Po is gonna get there.

781
00:41:56,814 --> 00:41:58,654
- Po's headed into trouble.
- Yeah.

782
00:41:59,884 --> 00:42:02,514
And this is a little...

783
00:42:04,355 --> 00:42:05,405
The stairs.

784
00:42:05,723 --> 00:42:07,453
It's probably the biggest laugh
in the movie.

785
00:42:07,859 --> 00:42:08,999
Yeah.

786
00:42:09,327 --> 00:42:11,377
And I think we made that atrium
originally, just like,

787
00:42:11,829 --> 00:42:13,559
it would be cool
to have this in the movie,

788
00:42:13,965 --> 00:42:17,335
and then as we kept working on the
movie, everybody started brainstorming:

789
00:42:17,969 --> 00:42:19,139
“How can we use this?”

790
00:42:19,437 --> 00:42:22,866
And I think that all led to the demise
of the whole tower, but...

791
00:42:23,508 --> 00:42:25,618
Il love that shot of looking up
at all those stairs.

792
00:42:26,077 --> 00:42:27,157
Oh, that's right.

793
00:42:27,478 --> 00:42:29,998
There was a whole pass early on
where we did not blow up the tower.

794
00:42:30,515 --> 00:42:33,035
No. Po got blown out of the tower.

795
00:42:33,551 --> 00:42:36,621
Yeah, they ran out of the tower
and they jumped into a sewer.

796
00:42:37,221 --> 00:42:38,361
Yeah.

797
00:42:40,725 --> 00:42:42,424
If it's that beautiful,
we gotta destroy it.

798
00:42:42,827 --> 00:42:43,937
Yeah.

799
00:42:45,596 --> 00:42:46,996
- Destroy.
- Yeah.

800
00:42:48,699 --> 00:42:51,189
This scene is one of the first times,
or one of the only times

801
00:42:51,702 --> 00:42:54,602
we had Jack Black and Gary Oldman
together to record.

802
00:42:55,173 --> 00:42:58,013
Yeah, imagine the universe imploding,
the two of those guys in the same room,

803
00:42:58,576 --> 00:43:02,116
riffing off each other.
That was pretty crazy.

804
00:43:02,780 --> 00:43:03,950
Yeah, it was really fun.

805
00:43:04,282 --> 00:43:06,362
The fact that they're both fans
of each other was pretty cool,

806
00:43:06,818 --> 00:43:09,538
and you could tell that they're
checking each other out,

807
00:43:10,088 --> 00:43:12,608
making sure they're doing a good
performance in front of the other one.

808
00:43:13,124 --> 00:43:15,754
And they came up with really good
ad-lib lines that we used for this.

809
00:43:16,294 --> 00:43:18,044
Yeah, the scene had been struggling
for a while and then we got

810
00:43:18,463 --> 00:43:20,363
the two of them together and they
just started working off each other.

811
00:43:20,798 --> 00:43:22,377
You get this energy between them, and...

812
00:43:22,767 --> 00:43:26,307
..they're similar enough to their
characters in real life, you know?

813
00:43:26,971 --> 00:43:28,811
Because Gary Oldman
is a little intimidating.

814
00:43:29,240 --> 00:43:32,109
Yeah, he's a little scary.
But, no, he’s a wonderful person,

815
00:43:32,710 --> 00:43:36,050
but he's scary like in a
performance set up. Oh, my gosh.

816
00:43:36,681 --> 00:43:38,551
He just becomes that intense,
you know, like on a dime,

817
00:43:38,983 --> 00:43:40,473
he'll just become that
intense peacock character.

818
00:43:40,885 --> 00:43:44,425
Yeah. This sequence batted through
a million different versions again,

819
00:43:45,089 --> 00:43:47,279
‘cause if you're having the good guy
and the bad guy meet for the first time,

820
00:43:47,758 --> 00:43:49,368
that's a pretty big event.

821
00:43:49,760 --> 00:43:53,480
And finally when Phil Craven cracked it,
he just went away into his room

822
00:43:54,165 --> 00:43:56,945
and we left him alone
for about two weeks, I think?

823
00:43:57,502 --> 00:43:58,432
Yeah.

824
00:43:58,736 --> 00:44:01,225
We didn't hear anything, see anything,
and then he comes out,

825
00:44:01,739 --> 00:44:05,429
and it is absolutely an amazing
sequence he just pulled out of ether.

826
00:44:06,110 --> 00:44:08,070
Yeah. Although, you know,
in any of these things,

827
00:44:08,513 --> 00:44:10,703
so many people work on it over time,
it's all these little bits and pieces,

828
00:44:11,182 --> 00:44:13,932
and it takes somebody to just...
finally pull them all together

829
00:44:14,485 --> 00:44:17,735
and create the final version,
just the great collaboration.

830
00:44:18,356 --> 00:44:21,136
Originally, this was
all taking place over dinner.

831
00:44:21,692 --> 00:44:25,122
- Dinner of deception.
- Dinner of deception.

832
00:44:25,730 --> 00:44:27,400
- Long ago...
- That was a great sequence.

833
00:44:27,798 --> 00:44:28,698
That was really funny.

834
00:44:29,000 --> 00:44:31,610
- And everybody was dying of poison.
- Yeah, everybody was dying...

835
00:44:32,870 --> 00:44:34,620
We killed a lot of people
on that version.

836
00:44:35,039 --> 00:44:38,579
Shen's trying to poison Po,
and Po's not eating the right poison,

837
00:44:39,243 --> 00:44:41,053
- he's eating everything else...
- Everybody else's food.

838
00:44:41,479 --> 00:44:42,649
Yeah.

839
00:44:44,549 --> 00:44:47,129
But that was when the peacock
was trying to be more stealthy.

840
00:44:47,652 --> 00:44:50,282
- He doesn't have to hide.
- Yeah.

841
00:44:51,489 --> 00:44:55,469
- Many different versions for that.
- This whole exchange here, I love it.

842
00:44:56,194 --> 00:44:57,804
Yeah, that was part of
the whole ad-libbing

843
00:44:58,196 --> 00:45:01,446
when the two of them were facing off
against each other in the same room.

844
00:45:02,066 --> 00:45:05,225
It just gives that energy between
the two of them. That was really cool.

845
00:45:05,836 --> 00:45:07,946
This scene's a great one
to really see the cannon, too,

846
00:45:08,406 --> 00:45:11,395
the design of the cannon
and what the inspiration for that was.

847
00:45:11,943 --> 00:45:14,223
Well, we always...
in our world, if we could,

848
00:45:14,712 --> 00:45:17,292
we wanted to push an animal theme,
and with the cannons,

849
00:45:17,815 --> 00:45:20,395
we actually pushed more towards,
like, these fire-breathing demons

850
00:45:20,918 --> 00:45:23,848
‘cause we wanted the lore

851
00:45:24,422 --> 00:45:27,492
of what Shen's doing
to kind of spread throughout the land.

852
00:45:28,092 --> 00:45:30,702
And you would, you would design things
to be more intimidating, you know.

853
00:45:31,229 --> 00:45:33,279
So, it fit perfectly, I think.

854
00:45:33,731 --> 00:45:37,391
We did that in the first film
with some of the equipment in the dojo.

855
00:45:38,069 --> 00:45:42,429
And then this one is just taking it
to a whole new level of just cool,

856
00:45:43,207 --> 00:45:45,377
you know, in demon technology.

857
00:45:46,510 --> 00:45:48,060
- Demon technology.
- Yeah.

858
00:45:48,446 --> 00:45:50,316
- Very cool.
- Yeah.

859
00:45:51,282 --> 00:45:53,972
And that whole action figure thing
in there,

860
00:45:54,518 --> 00:45:56,828
that was a tricky thing,
how to make sure that you could see it.

861
00:45:57,321 --> 00:45:58,281
And not see it, right?

862
00:45:58,589 --> 00:46:01,929
‘Cause you don't wanna blow the gag
for everybody until you have to.

863
00:46:02,560 --> 00:46:04,640
And I think we just moved the bars
enough apart

864
00:46:05,096 --> 00:46:08,196
for that one angle on Mantis’
little toy head

865
00:46:08,799 --> 00:46:10,989
and then the touch
of actually moving the head

866
00:46:11,469 --> 00:46:13,929
so everybody would realize
it was just, like, on a hinge.

867
00:46:14,438 --> 00:46:16,458
And then we have a big,
big story turn here

868
00:46:16,907 --> 00:46:18,867
where Po has another flashback
and makes a realization.

869
00:46:19,310 --> 00:46:21,330
This is the big pivot,
the really big pivot

870
00:46:21,779 --> 00:46:24,209
where everything
all comes together for Po,

871
00:46:24,715 --> 00:46:26,855
where this mission is now personal.

872
00:46:27,318 --> 00:46:29,598
And he's now off-balance as a master.

873
00:46:30,921 --> 00:46:32,290
And I think that shift was really...

874
00:46:32,657 --> 00:46:35,437
The whole point of that lead-up,
it's all fun and games until...

875
00:46:35,993 --> 00:46:38,133
..that moment where
everything changes for Po

876
00:46:38,596 --> 00:46:41,726
and he now has real reason
to be scared of the peacock.

877
00:46:42,333 --> 00:46:43,323
Yeah.

878
00:46:43,634 --> 00:46:46,824
And this whole thing,
this whole escape is to sort of show

879
00:46:47,438 --> 00:46:51,158
how Po is so off-balance that he's
putting his friends’ lives in danger.

880
00:46:51,842 --> 00:46:54,562
This was originally not meant
to have an exploding tower in it.

881
00:46:55,112 --> 00:46:56,342
No.

882
00:46:57,281 --> 00:47:01,471
No, but with the cannons being
developed more and then Peacock,

883
00:47:02,253 --> 00:47:04,973
and in almost everything,
Peacock's always ahead of Po.

884
00:47:05,523 --> 00:47:07,273
l love that addition to this story,

885
00:47:07,692 --> 00:47:10,272
that it made him
that much bigger of a threat.

886
00:47:10,795 --> 00:47:11,695
Right.

887
00:47:11,996 --> 00:47:13,956
And this is just a really
fun sequence in 3-D,

888
00:47:14,432 --> 00:47:16,801
and I know you worked a lot
with Damon to get that.

889
00:47:17,301 --> 00:47:19,141
Yeah, trying to make sure
that we get the scale,

890
00:47:19,603 --> 00:47:22,383
‘cause it's sometimes tricky when
you're pushing things really depthy.

891
00:47:22,940 --> 00:47:24,370
Things might become miniaturized.

892
00:47:24,775 --> 00:47:27,905
Damon was always very, very careful
to make sure that we kept the scale

893
00:47:28,512 --> 00:47:31,532
of this tower, so it feels like
this massive thing.

894
00:47:32,116 --> 00:47:33,956
