01:12:03,586 --> 01:12:06,626
and she somehow constructed that
to really hit you really hard.

1331
01:12:07,223 --> 01:12:10,323
The Wolf Boss has his
heroic moment there.

1332
01:12:10,927 --> 01:12:14,147
Yeah, he wasn't all bad.
He couldn't blow up his dudes.

1333
01:12:14,764 --> 01:12:18,834
Didn't we originally have a line
where he says, "I know that guy.

1334
01:12:19,602 --> 01:12:23,322
I play with his kids on Sundays"
or whatever. I forget.

1335
01:12:24,841 --> 01:12:26,591
We cut that line out.

1336
01:12:27,844 --> 01:12:29,774
At least he had a little character arc.

1337
01:12:31,314 --> 01:12:33,864
But he's not dead. He just fell off...

1338
01:12:34,383 --> 01:12:35,583
Yeah, I always wonder,
“Did he die? I don't know.”

1339
01:12:35,918 --> 01:12:38,758
- Does anybody really die in this world?
- 1 think the wolves are OK.

1340
01:12:39,322 --> 01:12:43,272
And the explosion, that explosion
of those gates is huge.

1341
01:12:43,993 --> 01:12:45,283
- Beautiful.
- Effects...

1342
01:12:45,628 --> 01:12:47,588
I love that they were
able to stylize it enough

1343
01:12:48,030 --> 01:12:51,809
so that it has that graphic punch,
you know, and not...

1344
01:12:52,501 --> 01:12:54,871
We were always on the edge of,
“Don't make it look like a gasoline..."

1345
01:12:55,371 --> 01:12:58,741
you know, like a real fire,
but it needs to have as much impact.

1346
01:12:59,375 --> 01:13:02,005
- Yeah.
- 1 thought they did that beautifully.

1347
01:13:02,545 --> 01:13:04,735
To have it be graphic
and have it be intense,

1348
01:13:05,214 --> 01:13:08,693
but still have some design to it
so it doesn't have to be so realistic.

1349
01:13:09,352 --> 01:13:10,932
Yeah, throughout the movie,
the explosions of the cannons

1350
01:13:11,320 --> 01:13:13,870
was a really visually unique
kind of cannon explosion.

1351
01:13:14,390 --> 01:13:15,440
David Tidgwell. Yep.

1352
01:13:15,758 --> 01:13:18,248
Incredible work with
the spiraling smoke plumes

1353
01:13:18,761 --> 01:13:24,271
and the trails of swirling sparks and
how all that works... It's incredible.

1354
01:13:25,201 --> 01:13:26,901
And then we take full advantage of it
here at the end of the movie,

1355
01:13:27,303 --> 01:13:32,373
‘cause we stage it in a darker sequence
that this light show just looks amazing.

1356
01:13:33,242 --> 01:13:36,312
The sound effects guys really worked
hard to get a unique sound for that.

1357
01:13:36,913 --> 01:13:40,392
Yeah, they want to make sure that
it wasn't, you know, recognizable.

1358
01:13:41,050 --> 01:13:42,070
It's a fireworks-based sound effect.

1359
01:13:42,385 --> 01:13:44,995
We wanted to make sure that
it was fizzy and different,

1360
01:13:45,488 --> 01:13:49,118
and it didn't sound Civil War or
World War Il or anything like that.

1361
01:13:49,792 --> 01:13:52,782
It was definitely
ancient-animal-run China.

1362
01:13:53,362 --> 01:13:56,052
Yeah, they went out to the desert
and they recorded all these explosions

1363
01:13:56,599 --> 01:13:58,679
- of fireworks and then...
- It was pretty cool.

1364
01:13:59,135 --> 01:14:00,365
..created a whole kind of unique sound

1365
01:14:00,703 --> 01:14:02,403
so there was that kind of
signature feeling to it.

1366
01:14:02,805 --> 01:14:03,915
Very unique.

1367
01:14:04,240 --> 01:14:08,340
That moment where Po is gathering
himself to reflect the cannon ball,

1368
01:14:09,078 --> 01:14:12,558
that was one that has
been around for a long time.

1369
01:14:13,182 --> 01:14:15,202
We had that in every version
of the final battle.

1370
01:14:15,651 --> 01:14:17,611
Yeah, it seems like that was the one
thing you knew from the beginning,

1371
01:14:18,054 --> 01:14:20,224
which was he was gonna
have to fight a cannon.

1372
01:14:20,690 --> 01:14:23,299
And it actually was
that second scene, you know.

1373
01:14:23,826 --> 01:14:26,666
There was the first scene that I boarded
and the second scene that Phil boarded

1374
01:14:27,229 --> 01:14:29,859
and that had, again, those elements
from the first movie

1375
01:14:30,399 --> 01:14:32,889
where the water test that you had,
Rodolphe.

1376
01:14:33,402 --> 01:14:36,712
And he had done that and that was
originally taking place in the village.

1377
01:14:37,340 --> 01:14:39,180
It wasn't in the midst of the battle.

1378
01:14:39,608 --> 01:14:42,948
But the problem with doing it all in
the village was it gave away everything.

1379
01:14:43,579 --> 01:14:46,919
He had nothing to resolve in
the battle, and there was no tension.

1380
01:14:47,583 --> 01:14:50,742
So this moment where he sees
the cannon finally coming to him

1381
01:14:51,354 --> 01:14:52,664
and he deflects it in that last moment

1382
01:14:53,022 --> 01:14:55,362
and you see the cannonball
turning into the water drop,

1383
01:14:55,858 --> 01:14:58,788
that was in every version...
of that final battle.

1384
01:14:59,362 --> 01:15:01,702
Yeah, you're putting those two
pieces together, resolving his past

1385
01:15:02,198 --> 01:15:05,268
and finding his inner strength in
this moment to defeat the cannonballs.

1386
01:15:05,868 --> 01:15:07,508
Really crucial piece of storytelling.

1387
01:15:07,903 --> 01:15:10,333
But I thought putting it
on that water setting just gave

1388
01:15:10,840 --> 01:15:12,770
that water drop even more resonance.

1389
01:15:13,209 --> 01:15:14,909
‘Cause you have the water on the fire,
as you said,

1390
01:15:15,311 --> 01:15:17,531
when you're doing
that visual development.

1391
01:15:18,014 --> 01:15:20,974
And, visually, it still takes advantage
of kind of what the desert scene did.

1392
01:15:21,550 --> 01:15:25,330
It was one guy and almost in the middle
of nowhere is gonna block a whole army.

1393
01:15:26,022 --> 01:15:29,622
And the fact that that just...
putting that one guy standing on water

1394
01:15:30,259 --> 01:15:31,549
and he's gonna...
What's he gonna do, you know?

1395
01:15:32,395 --> 01:15:34,855
Then you just have this amazing show
of how it plays out.

1396
01:15:35,364 --> 01:15:37,174
It was even more pathetic
with that little bit of flotsam

1397
01:15:37,600 --> 01:15:38,970
that he's standing on, you know?

1398
01:15:39,335 --> 01:15:42,525
Like a little wood boogie board that
he used to drag over there to...

1399
01:15:43,139 --> 01:15:44,399
Yeah.

1400
01:16:02,691 --> 01:16:04,331
This is a great scene
that Jon and Glenn wrote.

1401
01:16:04,727 --> 01:16:07,477
I think just a really fun,
interesting way

1402
01:16:08,030 --> 01:16:09,960
to kind of get at the final moment
between the two of them.

1403
01:16:10,399 --> 01:16:13,799
Great little dialogue between them where
he's talking about, you know, scars...

1404
01:16:14,437 --> 01:16:16,867
- Oh, yeah. Yeah, it's brilliant.
- It was just so funny.

1405
01:16:17,373 --> 01:16:19,043
‘Cause it's hitting the theme
and all of the issues,

1406
01:16:19,442 --> 01:16:22,052
but in such a kind of sideways way
that it's really entertaining.

1407
01:16:22,578 --> 01:16:26,648
It's almost the parody of the big final
moment of understanding speech

1408
01:16:27,383 --> 01:16:28,753
between the good guy and the bad guy.

1409
01:16:29,118 --> 01:16:33,658
But only Po could do that where
he really, honestly, is not equipped

1410
01:16:34,457 --> 01:16:36,627
for that kind of gravitas.

1411
01:16:37,093 --> 01:16:39,023
Yeah, there's just a brilliant piece
of animation from Dan

1412
01:16:39,462 --> 01:16:41,302
where he talks about
how his shoulders...

1413
01:16:41,730 --> 01:16:43,980
-"Keep the shoulders loose."
- It was really cute.

1414
01:16:44,467 --> 01:16:45,777
Yeah.

1415
01:16:46,135 --> 01:16:49,005
But it was also a challenge, too, to
make sure that Po comes off as sincere.

1416
01:16:49,572 --> 01:16:50,942
He's not making fun of
the peacock through all this.

1417
01:16:51,307 --> 01:16:53,206
- He sincerely wants to help him.
- Yeah.

1418
01:16:53,642 --> 01:16:56,662
And any pass that we did where Po came
off as being a little bit too goofy,

1419
01:16:57,246 --> 01:17:00,846
we had to dial back to make sure he
was deeply sincere through all this.

1420
01:17:01,517 --> 01:17:03,916
- Otherwise you don't like him.
- Yeah, he has to stay sweet.

1421
01:17:04,420 --> 01:17:06,700
That was always also the highest goal
of kung fu was to actually,

1422
01:17:07,223 --> 01:17:09,913
if you could fix your opponent, if you
could actually heal your opponent...

1423
01:17:10,459 --> 01:17:12,389
- Yeah.
-... that's the highest,

1424
01:17:12,828 --> 01:17:15,438
that's the best thing
you could ever try to do, so.

1425
01:17:15,965 --> 01:17:20,355
I always love that kind of message,
that Po is operating at that level.

1426
01:17:21,137 --> 01:17:22,307
But, yet, you still want them to fight.

1427
01:17:22,638 --> 01:17:24,478
Oh, yeah. You still gotta
see something blow up.

1428
01:17:24,874 --> 01:17:26,744
- You want the two of them to go at it.
- You still gotta do that.

1429
01:17:27,176 --> 01:17:29,016
That's the yin and yang of it.

1430
01:17:31,547 --> 01:17:33,097
And this little moment with Tigress...

1431
01:17:33,482 --> 01:17:35,292
That was one of the latest things
that we did.

1432
01:17:35,718 --> 01:17:37,738
One of the very last
animated shots that we did.

1433
01:17:38,187 --> 01:17:39,677
Yeah. It seems so obvious now
that of course

1434
01:17:40,089 --> 01:17:41,759
this is what would have to happen,
he'd have to hug her,

1435
01:17:42,158 --> 01:17:44,468
but we didn't think about
doing it till towards the end.

1436
01:17:44,960 --> 01:17:46,630
Yeah, wasn't that, again,
a cranky weekend thing?

1437
01:17:47,029 --> 01:17:48,289
I think it was another
one of your cranky weekends.

1438
01:17:48,631 --> 01:17:51,321
- 1 think you need more of those.
- 1 need more cranky weekends.

1439
01:18:18,027 --> 01:18:19,397
And this sequence, my goodness.

1440
01:18:19,762 --> 01:18:21,222
Yeah, then we get to go back
and see Dad, and...

1441
01:18:21,597 --> 01:18:23,467
- That kid gets a laugh every time.
- He's pretty miserable.

1442
01:18:23,899 --> 01:18:28,259
It's such a heart-tugging moment
to this,

1443
01:18:29,038 --> 01:18:33,397
and it was always hoped for that it
would be a deeply emotional moment.

1444
01:18:34,176 --> 01:18:36,426
And it was a matter of crafting
the subtleties on this

1445
01:18:36,912 --> 01:18:41,102
to get it to the point where
it could make you sort of choke up.

1446
01:18:41,850 --> 01:18:43,630
It's amazing, though, that
you leave him for a whole movie

1447
01:18:44,053 --> 01:18:45,693
and you come back and
that emotion’'s still there.

1448
01:18:46,088 --> 01:18:48,958
When you come back to this,
everybody is totally invested in what...

1449
01:18:49,525 --> 01:18:50,924
“What are they gonna
say to each other?"

1450
01:18:51,293 --> 01:18:54,133
It's only three scenes. The moment
where dad tells him he's adopted,

1451
01:18:54,697 --> 01:18:55,897
the moment where they say goodbye

1452
01:18:56,232 --> 01:18:57,542
and then the moment
where they make up at the end.

1453
01:18:57,900 --> 01:19:01,820
There's three sequences that their
entire relationship is hinged on.

1454
01:19:02,538 --> 01:19:04,727
Yeah. It's such a primal relationship.

1455
01:19:05,207 --> 01:19:08,137
You feel it tugging Po
throughout the movie and so,

1456
01:19:08,711 --> 01:19:11,961
knowing he's finally worked it out
is just such a release.

1457
01:19:12,781 --> 01:19:15,741
And I think the voice acting, both James
and Jack in this scene is just...

1458
01:19:16,318 --> 01:19:18,658
- Yeah. The way Jack just...
-..really beautiful.

1459
01:19:19,154 --> 01:19:23,224
...he just had so much emotion in his
voice, and I think that really inspired

1460
01:19:23,959 --> 01:19:26,129
William and Dan
when they did their animation.

1461
01:19:26,595 --> 01:19:28,325
l remember when you came back
from the recording session,

1462
01:19:28,731 --> 01:19:30,751
saying "You're not gonna believe it."

1463
01:19:32,067 --> 01:19:33,877
We cried in the recording booth,
and that doesn't happen very often.

1464
01:19:34,303 --> 01:19:35,173
We were like...

1465
01:19:35,471 --> 01:19:36,611
- We cried.
- Yeah.

1466
01:19:36,939 --> 01:19:39,599
And then you showed me...

1467
01:19:40,142 --> 01:19:43,482
We showed you the record and it
was put up against rough board and...

1468
01:19:44,113 --> 01:19:47,043
And even off the rough board
it's like... "Oh, gosh.”

1469
01:19:47,783 --> 01:19:49,363
It's so emotional.

1470
01:19:49,752 --> 01:19:51,892
And then Dan and William
got super excited

1471
01:19:52,388 --> 01:19:55,048
and they ran off and they did,
like Dan did all the Po shots

1472
01:19:55,591 --> 01:19:59,871
and William did all the Dad shots
and it was just so beautifully animated.

1473
01:20:27,690 --> 01:20:29,559
This shot was no easy feat.

1474
01:20:29,992 --> 01:20:32,622
Yeah, and everybody loves it.
They start clapping here.

1475
01:20:33,162 --> 01:20:35,092
And they go, "Wait a minute,
what's going on..."

1476
01:20:35,531 --> 01:20:36,791
“Where are we going?”

1477
01:20:37,132 --> 01:20:38,942
Matte painting. Look at this.
The length of China.

1478
01:20:39,368 --> 01:20:41,478
That's a matte painting feat.
That's insane.

1479
01:20:41,937 --> 01:20:43,166
Yeah.

1480
01:20:43,972 --> 01:20:46,192
Yeah, and you really wanna know
that you're going somewhere.

1481
01:20:46,675 --> 01:20:48,545
It's a really important story point
to get that sense of distance.

1482
01:20:48,977 --> 01:20:51,497
Jen kept pushing for distance.
“Il wanna feel like we're really moving

1483
01:20:52,014 --> 01:20:53,004
and getting out of here.”

1484
01:20:53,315 --> 01:20:55,275
Yeah, far, far. Not the next valley.

1485
01:20:55,718 --> 01:20:57,418
And that, you know,
looks like it might be Oogway there.

1486
01:20:57,820 --> 01:21:00,190
I love that. I don't even think
we thought of that misdirect

1487
01:21:00,689 --> 01:21:02,329
when we were kind of
originally working on it

1488
01:21:02,725 --> 01:21:04,365
and then as soon as we saw the shot,

1489
01:21:04,760 --> 01:21:06,900
people started saying,
“I thought that was Oogway.”

1490
01:21:07,363 --> 01:21:09,383
- It's great.
- And this is just... ] don't know.

1491
01:21:09,832 --> 01:21:13,202
l always get a little teary
on that spot, too, ‘cause it’s such a...

1492
01:21:13,836 --> 01:21:15,476
That's the shot that we

1493
01:21:16,038 --> 01:21:19,378
added later because it was
after we went to China.

1494
01:21:20,008 --> 01:21:21,758
- Yeah.
- And we saw how people

1495
01:21:22,177 --> 01:21:24,366
revered the panda so much.

1496
01:21:24,847 --> 01:21:27,657
Can't leave people thinking
that every panda in the world is dead.

1497
01:21:28,217 --> 01:21:29,767
- Yeah.
- There are kids going home, going,

1498
01:21:30,152 --> 01:21:33,112
-"Hey, Mommy, did all the pandas die?"
- Yeah.

1499
01:21:33,689 --> 01:21:35,769
- Just a downer.
- It's a little grim.

1500
01:21:36,225 --> 01:21:38,565
Yeah, we have to have
a few of them alive somewhere.

1501
01:21:39,061 --> 01:21:39,931
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

1502
01:21:40,229 --> 01:21:44,179
We used a little bit of architectural
reference and location reference

1503
01:21:44,900 --> 01:21:48,059
a little bit from that trip,
you know, from Qingchengshan again.

1504
01:21:48,670 --> 01:21:51,040
It was nice to kind of echo
that through that bit because

1505
01:21:51,540 --> 01:21:53,560
- that's where the pandas are from.
- Right.

1506
01:21:53,976 --> 01:21:55,286
There's a little something
written on the rock there.

1507
01:21:55,677 --> 01:21:57,607
Yeah. Yeah, it’s actually
the name of that mountain.

1508
01:21:58,046 --> 01:22:00,096
- Yeah. Little Easter egg.
- Yep.

1509
01:22:03,085 --> 01:22:05,695
And these end titles, also sort of a...

1510
01:22:06,221 --> 01:22:08,741
We always like bookending, right?
We like bookending our movies.

1511
01:22:09,258 --> 01:22:11,838
The first movie started with a 2-D
sequence and ended with a 2-D one.

1512
01:22:12,361 --> 01:22:16,201
And this one starts with the shadow
puppet sequence and ends with one.

1513
01:22:16,899 --> 01:22:20,619
And it was another fun one
to kind of figure out and work out.

1514
01:22:21,303 --> 01:22:23,323
Yeah, the guys at Shine created this

1515
01:22:23,772 --> 01:22:25,962
but Tang, I think,
did all the art himself.

1516
01:22:26,442 --> 01:22:27,932
I think he pretty much...

1517
01:22:28,310 --> 01:22:32,230
I think Jason...
Jason Brubaker did a couple also.

1518
01:22:32,948 --> 01:22:35,028
Tang was like booking,
trying to beat his baby being born.

1519
01:22:35,484 --> 01:22:40,704
He was expecting his son
and I was like, "I need this done.”

1520
01:22:41,590 --> 01:22:43,550
We're, like, full-blown in lighting.

1521
01:22:43,992 --> 01:22:45,072
He's like, "I hope she doesn't
have a baby right now.”

1522
01:22:45,360 --> 01:22:49,110
We're half-expecting him to be gone,
half painting.

1523
01:22:49,798 --> 01:22:52,548
And then I love these ideas
that the story team came up with

1524
01:22:53,101 --> 01:22:55,851
of what it might've been like to be
Po growing up in the Valley of Peace.

1525
01:22:56,405 --> 01:22:57,835
Januel.

1526
01:22:58,240 --> 01:23:01,050
Januel, who was one of the board guys,
came up with a lot of these scenarios,

1527
01:23:01,610 --> 01:23:03,860
and came up with quite a few,

1528
01:23:04,346 --> 01:23:07,825
and that inspired Tang to go
and make a lot of these images.

1529
01:23:08,484 --> 01:23:13,644
And the legend of how Po got,
you know, to Mr. Ping's back door,

1530
01:23:14,523 --> 01:23:16,573
Il love that whole
little bit of traveling

1531
01:23:17,025 --> 01:23:18,605
during the voice acting credits.

1532
01:23:18,994 --> 01:23:20,773
And you never know
what really happened.

1533
01:23:21,196 --> 01:23:22,596
No. Yeah.

1534
01:23:22,965 --> 01:23:24,715
Who knows, maybe it did
involve a volcano, but...

1535
01:23:25,133 --> 01:23:26,393
I think so.

1536
01:23:27,302 --> 01:23:28,972
- Surely.
- 1 believe it.

1537
01:23:31,139 --> 01:23:33,629
There's eating the bamboo furniture,
which was imported.

1538
01:23:34,142 --> 01:23:36,541
I do like seeing little
bits and pieces of that.

1539
01:23:37,045 --> 01:23:38,775
“It was imported, too.”

1540
01:23:41,183 --> 01:23:42,233
That was very cool.

1541
01:23:42,551 --> 01:23:43,811
Little Po.

1542
01:23:44,152 --> 01:23:45,522
- Yeah, we have long credits, don't we?
- We do.

1543
01:23:45,888 --> 01:23:47,198
We do. We have a lot of people
making these movies.

1544
01:23:47,556 --> 01:23:48,635
We try to make it look pretty, though,

1545
01:23:48,924 --> 01:23:51,354
so people will sit through
and watch all the credits.

1546
01:23:51,860 --> 01:23:54,670
Yeah and give the crew something to
kind of look at while they're looking

1547
01:23:55,230 --> 01:23:57,480
- for their name or whatever.
- Yeah, this was all done, finally,

1548
01:23:57,966 --> 01:23:59,636
I think, at the very,
very eleventh hour.

1549
01:24:00,035 --> 01:24:03,075
The last pass of this came in
right under the wire.

1550
01:24:03,672 --> 01:24:05,451
Credits are always the last thing,

1551
01:24:05,874 --> 01:24:08,094
‘cause otherwise
we might miss somebody.

1552
01:24:08,577 --> 01:24:10,327
I didn't help them either by...

1553
01:24:10,746 --> 01:24:13,026
You know, every transition
is actually an animating one,

1554
01:24:13,515 --> 01:24:16,205
so it's not like you can really
find a clean cut point to redo things.

1555
01:24:16,752 --> 01:24:19,562
So when they were re-rendering, there's
only three cuts to the whole thing.

1556
01:24:20,122 --> 01:24:22,022
And so when anything
had to be changed,

1557
01:24:22,491 --> 01:24:24,631
they re-rendered, basically,
a third of this thing.

1558
01:24:25,093 --> 01:24:27,233
And one of the things we decided
to do right during the mix, obviously,

1559
01:24:27,696 --> 01:24:29,626
right at the end of the movie,
was adding the song,

1560
01:24:30,065 --> 01:24:32,115
- or this remix by Junkie XL.
- Yeah.

1561
01:24:32,568 --> 01:24:33,938
And, again, it's a matter of tone.

1562
01:24:34,303 --> 01:24:36,553
It was after an
Angelina Jolie screening,

1563
01:24:37,039 --> 01:24:40,518
where she had brought all her kids
and afterward, her only comment was

1564
01:24:41,176 --> 01:24:43,166
“You know, you might want
to pick a really, really upbeat song.

1565
01:24:43,612 --> 01:24:44,632
Have you thought of a song yet?”

1566
01:24:44,947 --> 01:24:47,167
I thought, "Well, we haven't
had a song yet.”

1567
01:24:47,649 --> 01:24:49,349
Because in the first movie
we had a big, upbeat song,

1568
01:24:49,751 --> 01:24:51,091
but we didn't have one yet.

1569
01:24:51,453 --> 01:24:54,913
And so it was one of those
eleventh-hour things where Junkie XL

1570
01:24:55,557 --> 01:24:57,517
came in and came up with a remix for us

1571
01:24:57,960 --> 01:25:00,710
and it just had a nice,
happy, upbeat tone to it.

1572
01:25:01,263 --> 01:25:03,403
Yeah, and it really, like,
lifts your mood when you're coming out

1573
01:25:03,832 --> 01:25:06,702
and you connect back to baby Po
and the Po themes in a really fun way.

1574
01:25:07,269 --> 01:25:08,789
I think it helps a lot.

1575
01:25:09,171 --> 01:25:11,221
It celebrates the film in a great way,

1576
01:25:11,707 --> 01:25:14,137
and I love that the,
the way Shine put the art together

1577
01:25:14,643 --> 01:25:16,693
from the shadow puppet things
that we gave them,

1578
01:25:17,145 --> 01:25:19,955
it was just kind of focusing in
a little bit on

1579
01:25:20,515 --> 01:25:22,625
how these shadow puppets
were kind of created in art.

1580
01:25:23,085 --> 01:25:26,245
- It's a nice detail to show everybody.
- Yeah.

1581
01:25:26,855 --> 01:25:28,285
Yeah, there's so much gorgeous art
that gets created

1582
01:25:28,657 --> 01:25:31,407
over the course of these movies,
just infinite piles of art.

1583
01:25:31,960 --> 01:25:33,830
- It's staggering.
- Yeah.

1584
01:25:34,296 --> 01:25:35,636
Very cool.

1585
01:25:37,332 --> 01:25:39,552
We didn't get to talk
much about Guillermo.

1586
01:25:40,035 --> 01:25:41,995
- Would you like to?
- Yeah, like for instance,

1587
01:25:42,437 --> 01:25:45,277
the peacock... the peacock fighting.

1588
01:25:45,841 --> 01:25:49,271
I think he talked me out of
all the logic camera stuff,

1589
01:25:49,911 --> 01:25:51,991
‘cause I was always feeling
very sad that we had

1590
01:25:52,447 --> 01:25:54,617
a Mr. Burns of a peacock
who doesn't fight.

1591
01:25:55,083 --> 01:25:57,303
When we had all of that
cool action stuff, you know?

1592
01:25:57,786 --> 01:25:59,866
And you get stuck in the logic loop.

1593
01:26:00,322 --> 01:26:02,252
And he said,
“How can you have a martial arts movie

1594
01:26:02,691 --> 01:26:06,351
with a bad guy that doesn't
do martial arts? He's like Mr. Burns.

1595
01:26:07,029 --> 01:26:10,539
I mean, he's such a lame villain
if he can't do martial arts."

1596
01:26:11,199 --> 01:26:13,719
And I thought,
“You're absolutely right.”

1597
01:26:14,236 --> 01:26:16,635
And we have a villain
that was designed to do martial arts.

1598
01:26:17,139 --> 01:26:19,659
His initial concept is
that he should be a martial artist

1599
01:26:20,175 --> 01:26:23,745
who also has this thing that beats
everything he personally can do.

1600
01:26:24,413 --> 01:26:29,192
It's far more menacing if a guy
can beat something he understands

1601
01:26:30,018 --> 01:26:31,658
than can beat something
he can't understand.

1602
01:26:32,054 --> 01:26:32,924
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

1603
01:26:33,221 --> 01:26:36,181
Guillermo came in about halfway
through the moviemaking process

1604
01:26:36,758 --> 01:26:38,598
and really helped us
identify things like that

1605
01:26:39,027 --> 01:26:40,667
where we had maybe talked ourselves
out of good ideas.

1606
01:26:41,063 --> 01:26:42,353
Yeah. He said,
“Well, why don't you do this.”

1607
01:26:42,698 --> 01:26:44,038
I was like, "Well, we had
all these logic issues."

1608
01:26:44,399 --> 01:26:46,949
Like, “Well, forget that.”
I'm like, "Yes!

1609
01:26:47,869 --> 01:26:48,919
Let's do what's cool!"

1610
01:26:49,237 --> 01:26:50,347
He was the 14-year-old boy in the room

1611
01:26:50,672 --> 01:26:51,982
who was rooting
for it to be cool all the time.

1612
01:26:52,340 --> 01:26:54,090
Yeah, and that was such a breath
of fresh air.

1613
01:26:54,509 --> 01:26:56,879
He just was like always looking for,
“What's cool? What's cool?"

1614
01:26:57,379 --> 01:26:59,309
And I thought, "That's brilliant.”

1615
01:26:59,748 --> 01:27:02,298
Yeah. It's so valuable
to have just a fresh pair of eyes

1616
01:27:02,818 --> 01:27:05,658
and such a big-hearted person
come in and really kind of...

1617
01:27:06,221 --> 01:27:09,731
Yeah, and often it just brought back
what the movie was trying to be.

1618
01:27:10,392 --> 01:27:11,942
I mean, that's the thing
that he was really good at.

1619
01:27:12,294 --> 01:27:15,014
He didn't assert himself on the movie.

1620
01:27:15,564 --> 01:27:19,224
He was just very good at seeing
what the movie was asking for.

1621
01:27:19,901 --> 01:27:22,421
Just as a story, as...
what the characters are asking for.

1622
01:27:22,938 --> 01:27:25,368
He just looked at it and said,
“This is what it's screaming to be."

1623
01:27:25,874 --> 01:27:29,744
And I thought that was just so nice,
so invigorating.

1624
01:27:31,379 --> 01:27:35,279
And he, in a very short period of time,
came up with so many great ideas.

1625
01:27:35,984 --> 01:27:38,094
- Thanks for listening.
- Thank you very much.

1626
01:27:38,553 --> 01:27:39,423
- Thanks a lot.
- Thanks.

1627
01:27:39,721 --> 01:27:41,861
- We love talking, so it's great for us.
- Yeah.

1628
01:27:42,691 --> 01:27:43,951
Hang out.

1629
01:27:44,426 --> 01:27:45,536
Bye.

1630
01:27:46,328 --> 01:27:47,318
Bye.

1631
